      "content": "I apologize for the vagueness. Let's try to clarify. Quantum entanglement is indeed a bit like a \"magic trick\" because it defies our everyday intuition. In classical physics, objects are separate and their properties don't instantly influence each other unless they're physically connected. But in quantum mechanics, entangled particles behave as if they're connected by an invisible thread, and when you measure one particle, the other one seems to \"know\" and change its state instantly, no matter how far apart they are. This is what Einstein referred to as \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seems to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light, which is the universal speed limit in Einstein's theory of relativity.\n\nTo understand the mechanism, we can think of it like this: when two particles become entangled, their properties become linked in such a way that the state of one particle is dependent on the state of the other. This means that if you measure a property of one particle, like its spin, and find it to be up, the other particle, no matter how far away, will instantly be found to have the opposite spin down. This happens faster than the speed of light, which is why Einstein was",
